==English==

===Noun===

'''enmity'''

n. pl. en·mi·ties

#Deep-seated, often mutual hatred; a state of deep-seated ill-will. 
#The feeling of a hostile person, "Chris and Jamie could no longer contain their enmity".


compare, enemy: one who wishes or seeks to do ill toward another, a foe.


[Middle English enemite, from Old French enemistie, from Vulgar Latin *inimcits, from Latin inimcus, enemy.]

Synonyms (of enmity): hostility, antagonism, animosity, rancor, antipathy, animus

